Why EchoHarness replaces PiHarness at startup for now instead of both existing: AppState.harness is a single Arc<dyn Harness>, and PiHarness has no real image to launch (the noop WASM guest doesn't serve HTTP, so its endpoint_port is None, so the processor falls through to LlmRouter — which means launching it is ceremony with no payoff). EchoHarness is the thing that actually makes the conversation flow work end-to-end right now. The moment task 10 phase 2 lands a real pi WASM + wasi-sockets port forwarding, swapping back to PiHarness is one line in server::serve().

Why 'in-process' and not a subprocess: a subprocess would cost a fork/exec per agent, require the harness binary to be bundled separately, and add lifecycle complexity (PID tracking, signal handling). In-process axum server with per-agent TcpListener::bind('127.0.0.1:0') gives us: real ports, real isolation at the network level (the processor can't tell it's not a separate process), zero extra binary distribution. The ONE thing we lose is sandboxing — which the WASM path will restore.

Why the banner prepend: without it, users would see responses identical to the LlmRouter fallback, making 'is the harness actually running?' unanswerable by eye. Banner makes it visible: the first line of every response confirms harness involvement. When a real WASM harness is in place, its own prompt will replace this banner; the mechanism (prepend-system) can stay if useful.

Why the Arc<RwLock<Option<Arc<LlmRouter>>>> plumbing on EchoHandlerState: matches AppState's existing pattern where the LLM router can be replaced on config reload. If we held a snapshot Arc<LlmRouter>, the harness would silently stick to the pre-reload router forever. Reading through RwLock on each request means config changes flow to harness traffic immediately.

On host port: I use TcpListener::bind('127.0.0.1:0') which asks the kernel for an unused port. Alternative was to manage a port allocator in AppState — not worth it for <100 agents. 'Already running? Return existing record' check at top of launch() handles double-launch during reconciler cycles.

Why snapshot/restore aren't meaningful for EchoHarness: the demo harness has no persistent state (no workspace, no memory beyond its in-flight HTTP requests). The trait's default implementations (error for snapshot/restore, no-op for delete_snapshot) are the correct behavior. When this gets replaced by a real harness, those need real impls — already shipped for C2wHarness.
